30 of the most common port numbers categorized by their function:

Web and File Services
* 20 (TCP): FTP Data – Used for the actual transfer of file data.
* 21 (TCP): FTP Control – Used for sending commands and login information to a file server.
* 80 (TCP): HTTP – The standard port for unencrypted web traffic.
* 443 (TCP): HTTPS – The secure version of HTTP, using encryption (SSL/TLS) for safe web browsing.
* 8080 (TCP): HTTP Proxy – Often used as an alternative to port 80 or for web proxy services. [1, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8] 
Remote Access and Management
* 22 (TCP): SSH – Secure Shell; used for secure remote login and file transfers.
* 23 (TCP): Telnet – An older, unencrypted protocol for remote terminal access.
* 3389 (TCP): RDP – Remote Desktop Protocol; used to remotely control Windows computers.
* 5900 (TCP): VNC – Virtual Network Computing; another common protocol for remote desktop access.
* 2082/2083 (TCP): cPanel/SSL – Standard ports for managing web hosting via the cPanel interface. 
Email Services
* 25 (TCP): SMTP – Simple Mail Transfer Protocol; used primarily for sending email between servers.
* 110 (TCP): POP3 – Post Office Protocol; used by email clients to retrieve messages from a server.
* 143 (TCP): IMAP – Internet Message Access Protocol; allows users to access and manage email stored on a server.
* 465 (TCP): SMTPS – Secure SMTP for encrypted email sending.
* 587 (TCP): SMTP Submission – The modern port for email clients to submit outgoing mail.
* 993 (TCP): IMAPS – Secure IMAP over SSL/TLS.
* 995 (TCP): POP3S – Secure POP3 over SSL/TLS. 
Network Infrastructure
* 53 (TCP/UDP): DNS – Domain Name System; translates human-readable domain names (e.g., google.com) into IP addresses.
* 67/68 (UDP): DHCP – Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol; automatically assigns IP addresses to devices on a network.
* 123 (UDP): NTP – Network Time Protocol; synchronizes the clocks of computers across a network.
* 161/162 (UDP): SNMP – Simple Network Management Protocol; used for monitoring and managing network devices like routers and switches. 
Directory and Database Services
* 389 (TCP/UDP): LDAP – Lightweight Directory Access Protocol; used for accessing central directory services.
* 445 (TCP): SMB/CIFS – Server Message Block; used for file and printer sharing in Windows environments.
* 1433 (TCP): MSSQL – Default port for Microsoft SQL Server database connections.
* 1521 (TCP): Oracle – Default port for Oracle database listeners.
* 3306 (TCP): MySQL – Standard port for MySQL and MariaDB databases.
* 5432 (TCP): PostgreSQL – Default port for PostgreSQL databases. 
Specialized Communication
* 500 (UDP): ISAKMP – Used for establishing security associations (VPN tunnels) in IPsec.
* 1194 (UDP/TCP): OpenVPN – The standard port for OpenVPN virtual private network services.
* 5060 (TCP/UDP): SIP – Session Initiation Protocol; used for initiating VoIP (Voice over IP) and video calls. 


